---
import Doc from '../../layouts/Doc.astro';
import Callout from '../../components/Callout.astro';
import CommandPager from '../../components/CommandPager.astro';
import { url } from '../../lib/url';

const title = 'mcp';
const description =
  'Design an MCP setup with least-privilege, human-in-the-loop, and centralised auditing. Tier the servers. Name the credentials. Write a policy an auditor would accept.';
---

<Doc title={title} description={description} section="commands">
  <p class="doc-lede">
    Before any agent gets write access to a real system, the access pattern
    has to be designed. <code>mcp</code> does not stand up servers for you. It
    produces the configuration and the policy that tells the team how to
    implement them safely, and how an auditor would expect to see them.
  </p>

  <h2>Why this command exists</h2>
  <p>
    The Model Context Protocol has become the "USB-C port for AI": the
    standard way agents reach real systems. That makes it the largest attack
    surface and the largest source of operational risk in an AI-first stack.
    Get it wrong and an unscoped credential or a missing confirmation modal
    becomes the incident headline.
  </p>
  <p>
    Most teams build MCP servers the way they build internal tools: one
    server, all the tools, one credential, "we will figure out auditing
    later". <code>mcp</code> exists to stop that. It walks the
    <a href={url('foundation/mcp-principles/')}>three non-negotiables</a>
    (least-privilege binding, human-in-the-loop, centralised auditing) and
    produces config files and a policy doc that operationalise them from the
    first day.
  </p>

  <Callout label="Read first" tone="ember">
    <p>
      The full argument is in
      <a href={url('foundation/mcp-principles/')}>MCP principles</a>. The
      <a href={url('blueprint/#mcp')}>2026 Blueprint</a> section on MCP gives
      the industry context.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2>When to reach for it</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Before connecting an agent to a production database, deploy pipeline, payments system, or anything customer-facing.</li>
    <li>Before exposing destructive operations (DELETE, refunds, sends).</li>
    <li>When the security team asks "what does the agent have access to?" and the answer is "everything".</li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('commands/audit/')}><code>audit</code></a> flagged an
      ungated MCP config.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What it produces</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <code>.context/mcp-config.json</code>: a starter configuration in
      standard MCP host format, scoped to the four tiers.
    </li>
    <li>
      <code>docs/mcp-policy.md</code>: the human-readable policy that names
      which tiers exist, which actions require HITL, who can attach which
      servers, and where audit logs live.
    </li>
    <li>
      Optionally, individual <code>mcp-server-&lt;name&gt;.config.json</code>
      stubs for each server tier.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Inventory the systems.</strong> Which systems does the agent
      need to interact with? Which are read vs write? Who is the agent
      identity, service account or user impersonation? "Just hook it up to
      everything" is politely refused.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Sort into four tiers.</strong> Tier 1 context (read-only,
      low-risk). Tier 2 internal write. Tier 3 production read. Tier 4
      production write. Placement is shown to you before anything is generated.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Name the tools.</strong> Verb plus qualifier:
      <code>read_payment_by_id</code>, <code>refund_payment_to_customer</code>.
      The blast radius is visible in the name.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Configure HITL in the config, not the prompt.</strong> Every
      Tier 4 tool gets <code>requiresConfirmation: true</code>. The policy
      doc names the modal, the approvers, and the audit trail.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Configure auditing.</strong> Every server has a named log
      destination: a specific system, not "TBD". Alerting rules: tools
      invoked outside business hours, sensitive parameter patterns, failure
      spikes, new tool combinations.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Configure credentials.</strong> One credential per tier, scoped
      to the smallest possible role, stored in a named secret manager. The
      config references env var names, never literal secrets.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Cross-link.</strong>
      <code>AGENTS.md</code> gets a pointer to the policy (in its "See also"
      section) so the agent can find it when it asks "can I do X?".
    </li>
  </ol>

  <Callout label="The quality bar" tone="mute">
    <p>
      Every server is in exactly one tier. Every Tier 4 tool has
      <code>requiresConfirmation: true</code>. Every server has a named audit
      destination. No credentials in the config file (only env var
      references). The policy file is something an auditor would accept, not
      a vibe.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2>Failure modes the command guards against</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>One server, all tiers.</strong> Hard no. Split.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>HITL via prompt instruction.</strong> "Tell the agent to ask
      first" is not a security control. Enforce in config.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Audit "TBD".</strong> If you cannot name the destination, the
      system is not ready for the agent. Push back.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Credentials in the repo.</strong> Never. Even for testing.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Related ideas</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/mcp-principles/')}>MCP principles</a>. The
      three non-negotiables and the four-tier server layout.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/anti-patterns/')}>Anti-patterns</a> #5:
      over-exposing tools.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/five-layer-stack/')}>The five-layer stack</a>.
      Tooling is its own layer for a reason.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('blueprint/#mcp')}>2026 Blueprint: MCP in production</a>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <CommandPager slug="mcp" />
</Doc>
